DTSTART:20260416T230000Z
DTEND:20260417T010000Z
SUMMARY:Myth\, Ritual and Resistance: A Georgian Wine Tasting
DESCRIPTION:Wine &amp\; the Divine: An Evening of Georgian Wine\, Myth &amp
 \; MemoryWhat is the connection between wine and the divine?Georgia — th
 e so-called Cradle of Wine — has treated wine as a sacred substance for 
 nearly 8\,000 years. Join us for the very first guided wine tasting social
  at the Lighthouse\, an evening that travels deep into Eurasia and into an
 cient stories that are still very much alive.Tonight\, under the guidance 
 of educator Sam Hewiit\, we'll treat wine as a medium. Viewed in this way\
 , Georgian wine carries cultural history directly to the senses. Together\
 , we'll explore the mystic world of Georgian wine — tasting\, talking\, 
 and sharing what we discover when we pair the delight of these wines with 
 learning for an all encompassing experience.We'll explore:The birthplace o
 f wineWine as the meeting point between gods and humansCultural preservati
 on across millenniaHow lessons of independence and resistance speak to our
  world todayThe evening opens with an intimate hour of guided tasting in s
 mall groups. Then we open it up — a wine-fueled social hour to keep the 
 conversation going.Educator Sam Hewitt will guide us through the history\,
  myth\, and mysticism surrounding this remarkable culture and Natural wine
  purveyors Jenny &amp\; Francois will provide us with various Georgian bot
 tles for us to delight in. As the Venetian ambassador Contarini wrote in t
 he late Middle Ages: "Georgians consider the abundance of wine to be the b
 est marker of hospitality."We hope you'll find us at Olio Lighthouse to be
  extremely hospitable.Wine and snacks included in the ticket price. Resour
 ces provided: where to buy Georgian wine and tasting notes from the evenin
 g.\n\nTickets & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/myth_ritual_and_resi
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/myth_ritual_and_resi
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cec92a80-9a05-4696-9c7d-5e16e1949e3c@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260413T141039Z
DTSTART:20260419T170000Z
DTEND:20260419T190000Z
SUMMARY:Thawing Out: A Sensory Wake Up for Spring
DESCRIPTION:"As we reacquaint ourselves with our breathing bodies\, then th
 e perceived world itself begins to shift and transform." — David Abram\,
  The Spell of the SensuousYour body knows what to do and sometimes we just
  need a little nudge and a place to block out the distractions. This is a 
 special 2-hour Sunday Olio designed to step out of the city buzz and into 
 your own body.&nbsp\;Join us on Sunday\, April 19th for a chance to thaw o
 ff the winter blues and attune your body and mind for spring time.In a cit
 y that never stops\, it's easy to lose the thread of the seasons entirely.
  But we are seasonal creatures and our bodies are happy when we acknowledg
 e the changes and start to alter our rhythms.&nbsp\;Alice and Julie\, incr
 edible facilitators with decades of experience between them\, will guide u
 s through an experience that brings us back into our senses and back into 
 a feeling of connection. Through an array of practices drawn from ecophilo
 sophy\, somatics\, natural science\, spirituality\, and movement\, they'll
  help you attune intellectually\, physically\, and spiritually.&nbsp\;We'l
 l deep dive into questions we take for granted — like\, what even is the
  body? — and discover what becomes possible when we stop rushing past th
 em long enough to actually feel the answer.What to expect:The best way to 
 shift perspective is to start from innocence — evoking the genuine and o
 pen curiosity that arises when we're willing to put aside what we think we
  know and explore with fresh eyes.In the words of Zen teacher Shunryu Suzu
 ki\, "In the beginner's mind there are many possibilities\, but in the exp
 ert's there are few."Afternoon flow:Beginner's Mind: Discovering what we c
 an know about the body and community from different angles (in small and l
 arge groups) Beginner's Body: Waking the senses with a (fun!) guided indiv
 idual exploration Beginner's Heart: Moving toward the longing for communit
 y that includes self and other. A series of facilitated individual and col
 lective movements that will help us build the skills to participate in the
  field of what we truly wish for.*Wear clothing in which you can breathe a
 nd move easily. We will learn and play in simple ways that are accessible 
 for all bodies.Your guides:Julie Harris is a lover of weaving together div
 erse streams of wisdom to yield rich and surprising forms of aliveness and
  nourishment. Her work as a coach\, breathwork facilitator and teacher is 
 influenced by adventures in the natural world\; pilgrimage to India and Eg
 ypt\; the power of language\, story\, and mythology\; and a wide range of 
 individual and communal spiritual practices. She deeply trusts the innate 
 intelligence of each person and the creativity that arises to meet whateve
 r is needed in the moment. riverbendcoaching.comAlice Wells is committed t
 o the possibility of a generative\, sustainable\, and just world through a
  collective awakening to our interconnectedness with all life. She brings 
 more than thirty years of experience working therapeutically and integrati
 vely with people seeking to live fully\, drawing on Eastern and Western ph
 ilosophy\, medicine and spiritual traditions\, Depth Psychology\, voice\, 
 dance and movement\, bodywork\, ritual\, breathwork\, and other transforma
 tional practices. onebreathcircle.org\n\nTickets & info: https://www.viewc
 y.com/event/thawing_out_a_sensor
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/thawing_out_a_sensor
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:449221e1-ca4d-4167-b848-465cd5b1d271@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260413T141039Z
DTSTART:20260422T230000Z
DTEND:20260423T013000Z
SUMMARY:Lighthouse Cinema: Agnes Varda 
DESCRIPTION:Join the very first Lighthouse Cinema night! Popcorn and a drin
 k included in your ticket &lt\;3 &nbsp\;Pioneering filmmaker Agnès Varda 
 made The Gleaners &amp\; I in her early seventies — a time when personal
  reinvention can feel like either an existential burden or a dire imperati
 ve. Both the film's subject — individuals who collect crops left behind 
 by commercial farming\, known as gleaners — and its form\, a fragmentary
  personal essay\, were uncommon for their time. Certainly not the expected
  territory for a filmmaker with as important a legacy as Varda\, one of th
 e founders of the Left Bank\, a left-wing offshoot of the French New Wave.
 What stands out is not only the seriousness with which Varda investigates 
 the corrosive effects of capitalism\, overconsumption\, and prejudice in r
 ural and urban France at the turn of the millennium — but the playfulnes
 s with which she inserts herself into the conversation\, aided by the spon
 taneous possibilities of her new digital camera. Amidst the world's mounti
 ng crises\, it feels remarkable to watch a film so steeped in personal dis
 covery and formal experimentation that never once feels glib about them.A 
 perfect film to open our curated cinema series — hang out afterwards for
  a social moment to pour a drink and talk about what we just watched toget
 her.&nbsp\;Doors open at 7:00pm&nbsp\;Film kicks off at 7:30pm&nbsp\;Chill
  and chat from 8:50-9:30ish&nbsp\;\n\nTickets & info: https://www.viewcy.c
 om/event/lighthouse_cinema_ag
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/lighthouse_cinema_ag
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:47fa4935-1ec2-4c24-a040-86138778a90b@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260413T141039Z
DTSTART:20260423T233000Z
DTEND:20260424T010000Z
SUMMARY:Abolition\, Misconceptions\, and the Myth of the “Bad Guy”
DESCRIPTION:In progressive circles\, many people say they support abolition
 . After George Floyd’s murder in 2020\, the word moved from the margins 
 into mainstream discourse—appearing in hashtags\, op-eds\, city council 
 debates\, and donation pages. But saying the word and understanding what i
 t asks of us are very different things.For some\, abolition is imagined si
 mply as the disappearance of prisons and police. In progressive spaces\, i
 t can also function as a kind of political shorthand\, signaling agreement
  without fully understanding the ideas underneath it. But abolition is not
  only about removing institutions. It is about transforming the culture th
 at made those institutions seem necessary in the first place. As Angela Da
 vis reminds us\, abolition is not only about changing institutions—it’
 s about changing our ideas.Drawing on contemporary data and original resea
 rch with people working within the criminal legal system\, as well as thos
 e who have been directly impacted by it\, this Olio will complicate the st
 ories we tell about harm\, safety\, and accountability. We will examine ho
 w these narratives operate at an institutional level\, but this is also an
  opportunity to look at how we have internalized them and may be unconscio
 usly enacting them in our day-to-day lives. For instance\, we’ll explore
  how the category of the “bad guy” is constructed\, how carceral cultu
 re shapes even progressive movements\, and why many of us struggle to imag
 ine accountability beyond punishment.Using Dr. Henson’s Eight Acknowledg
 ements of Abolition\, this lecture moves beyond slogans to ask harder ques
 tions about justice\, responsibility\, and safety\, and explores what abol
 ition might actually look like in practice.Following the talk\, we’ll mo
 ve into a social hour for a chance to meet others in the room. Through pro
 mpts and questions\, we’ll continue the conversation together\, creating
  an opportunity to form connections within community and to carry some of 
 the evening’s insights into our daily lives.Our teacher:&nbsp\;Abigail H
 enson\, Ph.D.\, strives to reshape how we talk about criminal justice. As 
 a scholar\, researcher\, and podcast host\, she explores the human stories
  behind the statistics\, examining how the criminal legal system affects r
 eal people\, their communities\, and their sense of self. Her work spans i
 nterviewing criminal legal agents and analyzing how language shapes law en
 forcement culture\, as well as writing about and teaching abolition by exp
 loring what it means to imagine justice beyond punishment. Her mission is 
 to challenge outdated narratives and break down stigma by putting people a
 t the center of the conversation and shining a light on systemic injustice
 .\n\nTickets & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/reshaping_our_systems
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/reshaping_our_systems
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:a1e8c99e-6c82-44f4-bed8-61004b83e46b@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260413T141039Z
DTSTART:20260428T230000Z
DTEND:20260429T010000Z
SUMMARY:Practicing Presence: Mindfulness for a Meaningful Life
DESCRIPTION:Practicing Presence is a four-week mindfulness course designed 
 to help you build a meditation practice that genuinely fits into your life
 —and into the world you live in.We'll meet on four consecutive Tuesday e
 venings from 7–9 PM at the Olio Lighthouse\, beginning April 28.This ser
 ies is for people who are curious about mindfulness\, have tried meditatin
 g before but struggled to sustain a practice\, or are looking for a ground
 ed and supportive way to deepen their relationship with themselves\, other
 s\, and the wider world.We’ll meet as a small sangha of no more than 12 
 people\, creating space for real relationships\, personalized guidance\, a
 nd meaningful conversation.Over four weeks\, you will:Learn foundational m
 indfulness meditation practicesBuild a realistic daily meditation habit us
 ing behavioral science toolsExplore how mindfulness relates to emotions\, 
 relationships\, and the wider worldReceive personalized guidance in a smal
 l group (max 12 people)Leave with a sustainable practice and resources for
  continuing at homeMany people are drawn to meditation because they want m
 ore calm\, clarity\, and presence. They read about mindfulness\, download 
 apps\, attend occasional classes—and still find it difficult to practice
  consistently.This course addresses that gap directly. By integrating cont
 emplative practice with insights from behavioral science\, we focus on bui
 lding a steady\, realistic mindfulness practice that can be sustained in e
 veryday life.Rather than emphasizing extraordinary states in retreat setti
 ngs\, the series centers on what matters most: developing presence in the 
 places it counts—your work\, relationships\, body\, emotions\, and daily
  routines.What You'll ReceiveThis course combines contemplative tradition 
 with practical tools for real life.Guided meditation and teachings: Weekly
  instruction grounded in established mindfulness traditions.Behavioral sci
 ence tools for habit building: Practical strategies to help meditation bec
 ome a consistent part of your daily life.Engaged mindfulness: Exploring ho
 w contemplative practice supports compassionate action without burnout or 
 bypassing.One-on-one mentorship: Each participant receives a private 15-mi
 nute consultation to discuss their practice\, goals\, and challenges.Perso
 nalized practice plan: You'll develop a realistic approach to building min
 dfulness into your schedule and routines.Practice resources: Reflection pr
 ompts and audio recordings of guided meditations for home practice.Weekly 
 micro-challenges: Small experiments for integrating mindfulness into daily
  life—your commute\, meetings\, relationships\, and conversations.The go
 al is simple: not just to learn about mindfulness\, but to leave with a pr
 actice that is already part of your life.Weekly ArcWeek 1: Introduction to
  Mindfulness — body\, breath\, and foundationsWeek 2: Mindfulness of Emo
 tions — meeting experience with compassionWeek 3: The Wise Heart — cul
 tivating kindness\, balance\, and resilienceWeek 4: Bringing Practice into
  the World — relationships\, work\, and daily lifeEach session includes 
 guided meditation\, short teachings\, group reflection\, and practical sup
 port for building a home practice.About the TeacherThis course is taught b
 y Britt Titus\, who is in her second year of a meditation teacher training
  program under Jack Kornfield and Tara Brach.Britt has practiced meditatio
 n since childhood—including a formative period living at an ashram in In
 dia at age nine.Her work brings together three perspectives: contemplative
  practice\, behavioral science\, and humanitarian work in crisis-affected 
 regions around the world. Her teaching focuses on helping people develop m
 editation practices that are both deeply rooted and practically sustainabl
 e in the midst of everyday life.Who This Is ForThis course is open to begi
 nners and experienced meditators alike\, especially those who want:A groun
 ded introduction to mindfulnessSupport building a consistent meditation pr
 acticeA small in-person learning communityPractical tools for integrating 
 mindfulness into daily lifeNo prior meditation experience or spiritual bac
 kground is required.&nbsp\;*No worries if you have to miss a week\, we wil
 l make sure you are caught up with any materials provided during class.Sch
 olarshipsWe have a small number of scholarship spots available for those f
 acing financial barriers. If cost is preventing you from participating\, p
 lease email brittknee007@gmail.com with a short note about why this course
  would be meaningful for you. Scholarships are offered on a first-come fir
 st-serve\, rolling basis.\n\nTickets & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/
 practicing_presence
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/practicing_presence
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bbd41527-08b8-43cc-8e7a-0d17bc86003c@viewcy.olio
