SUMMARY:Dial-up Disco: An Olio House Party
DESCRIPTION:Tickets:This is a member celebration!&nbsp\; To attend this par
 ty you can sign up for our monthly membership which gives you 2 free event
 s each month. &nbsp\;You will then be able to invite one friend to the par
 ty &lt\;3&nbsp\;It's our 11th anniversary and the parents are away\, so we
 're throwing a party.Whether you were at the first living room class with 
 a professor in 2015 or this is your first time hearing about this communit
 y\, we want to celebrate 11 years of Olio with you.We're playfully leaning
  back into the joy and wonder of the dial-up era (this is what happens whe
 n you let 5 millennials plan a party).What to expect:7:30pm: Upon arrival 
 we match you with a group of friends based on our secret witchery\, i.e.\,
  whoever we think you should meet after a 1-minute conversation8pm: You si
 t with your new friends and discuss a couple of curated prompts related to
  the dial-up era9-11pm: DJ SASA plays '90s and early 2000s hits and we dan
 ce our asses offTake dance breaks to bedazzle\, yo-yo\, and make art (reme
 mber that rainbow scratch-off paper?!)Pop-Tarts\, pizza bites\, and childh
 ood cereals fuel our energy throughout the night12-1am: We'll wind down wi
 th tea and stretches and ambient music because we love our bodiesAttire:Dr
 ess how you dressed when you were 11. Or how you wish you dressed!Tickets:
 This is a member celebration! To attend this party you can sign up for our
  monthly membership which gives you 2 free events each month. &nbsp\;You w
 ill then be able to invite one friend to the party &lt\;3&nbsp\;What is Th
 ink Olio?Think Olio is an ongoing experiment in lifelong learning. We are 
 a community of open-minded people who gather to exchange ideas with new fr
 iends and connect over art\, literature\, and philosophy.An Olio is what w
 e call the social learning events we’ve been organizing since 2015. A bl
 end between a lecture and a house party\, Olios are led by a teacher who l
 oves sharing their passions and the room is filled with curious\, open-min
 ded New Yorkers.&nbsp\;Six months into creating a venue\, one of our favor
 ite feelings has been the moments where we’ve stepped outside of time. W
 e’ve created a space where conversations don’t feel rushed\, people ar
 e greeted with hugs\, and as a community\, we spontaneously come up with n
 ew ideas (like the dial-up-disco house party) and bring them to life.Our g
 oal is to spark new perspectives\, ignite curiosity\, and enjoy ourselves 
 socially—an alternative to typical nightlife options.Check out our full 
 calendarDisclaimer: By purchasing a ticket\, you agree to have your photo/
 video used for social media/marketing materials. If you prefer to not have
  your photo taken\, feel free to send us a note.\n\nTickets & info: https:
 //www.viewcy.com/event/member_disco
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/member_disco
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:79de1303-e44a-4d37-a012-a12c6eb2baf7@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260413T141039Z
DTSTART:20260514T233000Z
DTEND:20260515T010000Z
SUMMARY:Codependence with Capitalism: Attachment styles beyond romance 
DESCRIPTION:From our earliest relationships\, many of us learned that belon
 ging requires compliance. These childhood attachment wounds don't stay in 
 childhood\, they follow us into our romantic relationships\, our friendshi
 ps\, and our codependency with the capitalist system we're embedded in.Led
  by depth psychologist\, Dene Logan\, this Olio looks at how codependency 
 shapes our experience of community\, often without our awareness.&nbsp\;Re
 lationships\, romantic to communal\, are something more and more of us are
  choosing to opt out of entirely. But what we risk losing is the most irre
 placeable part of our humanity: our imagination and our capacity for empat
 hy.As technology reshapes human interaction at a pace we've never encounte
 red before\, the cost of this kind of relating is becoming impossible to i
 gnore.&nbsp\;How have institutions deepened our codependency with capitali
 sm and narrowed our perception of difference as something beneficial? What
  does belonging look like when it no longer requires our conformity? And h
 ow do we heal the attachment wounds that made codependent relating\, in ou
 r romantic relationships and beyond\, feel like the only option?We’ll ex
 plore ways to build connection from a place of sovereignty rather than sca
 rcity and have plenty of time for discussion as the evening unfolds into a
 n intimate house party after the lecture.Our teacher for the evening:Dené
  Logan is an LA-based Marriage and Family Therapist\, depth psychologist\,
  and author of Sovereign Love. A mentee of renowned couples therapist Esth
 er Perel and co-host of the What’s My 100%? podcast\, Dené's work sits 
 at the intersection of soul psychology\, attachment\, and the relational p
 atterns that shape how we move through the world — from our most intimat
 e romantic bonds to the communities we inhabit.Evening Flow7:30 PM – Doo
 rs open. Settle in\, grab a drink\, and meet a friend.8:00 PM – The Olio
  begins: an intimate\, interactive lecture and guided exploration.9:15 PM 
 – Instead of a traditional Q&amp\;A\, we shift into a social experience
 —discussing ideas with others in the room while the teacher joins and fl
 oats between conversations.10:00 PM - Last call at the bar and we'll start
  to wind down the evening.What Is an Olio?Think Olio is an ongoing experim
 ent in lifelong learning. We are a community of open-minded people who gat
 her to exchange ideas with new friends and connect over art\, literature\,
  and philosophy.Check out our full calendarOur $25 membership gives you tw
 o events for the price of one!&nbsp\;An Olio is what we call the social le
 arning events we’ve been organizing since 2015. A blend between a lectur
 e and a house party\, Olios are led by a teacher who loves sharing their p
 assions and the room is filled with curious\, open-minded New Yorkers.&nbs
 p\;Our goal is to spark new perspectives\, ignite curiosity\, and enjoy ou
 rselves socially—an alternative to typical nightlife options.Disclaimer:
  By purchasing a ticket\, you agree to have your photo/video used for soci
 al media/marketing materials. If you prefer to not have your photo taken\,
  feel free to send us a note. Photo by Zhi-Da Zhong\n\nTickets & info: htt
 ps://www.viewcy.com/event/codependence_with_cap
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/codependence_with_cap
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:3362d2ac-4dc2-43ac-bb06-22bcd85a95c5@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260413T141039Z
DTSTART:20260522T140000Z
DTEND:20260529T210000Z
SUMMARY:OlioTrip Morocco: Music\, Spirit & Living Tradition
DESCRIPTION:OlioTrip Morocco: Music\, Spirit &amp\; Living Tradition&nbsp\;
 May 22–29\, 2026OverviewThis OlioTrip\, curated in collaboration with LI
 LA and led by Moroccan Gnawa musician Samir Langus\, offers an immersive e
 xperience of Morocco through the interconnected lenses of music\, culture\
 , and spirituality. As always\, our trips are designed as a relational\, p
 lace-based immersion - the kind of trip that only happens when you are mov
 ing around with locals. Traversing from the Atlantic coast to historic por
 t cities and into the rural countryside\, Samir and the people of LILA and
  Olio will curate the experience every step of the way so that you can let
  go and fully enjoy every step of cobblestone and each wave of the Atlanti
 c.&nbsp\;Our group will engage with Morocco through sound\, story\, and li
 ved tradition: exploring Gnawa music and its spiritual roots\, learning ab
 out Morocco’s interwoven Muslim and Jewish histories\, and connecting wi
 th local ecological practices. Throughout the week our activities will emp
 hasizes depth\, presence\, and cultural exchange\, creating space for both
  learning and integration.Rough ItineraryMay 22–24: AgadirThe journey be
 gins in Agadir\, a coastal gateway where contemporary Morocco meets long-s
 tanding tradition. We ease into the experience through the relaxed surf cu
 lture and beach village life of Taghazoute\, offering time to acclimate an
 d connect with the sea.Our group will then travel to the hometown of our g
 uide\, Samir Langus\, for an intimate\, family-style welcome! This gatheri
 ng centers Moroccan hospitality\, shared meals\, and a live musical experi
 ence\, offering a rare introduction to local life through personal relatio
 nships. This opening chapter sets the tone for the week\, but it will be h
 ard to leave this relaxing beach town.May 24–27: EssaouiraEssaouira has 
 long been a crossroads of cultures\, shaped by African\, Arab\, Amazigh\, 
 and Jewish influences. Known for its windswept ramparts\, artistic spirit\
 , and historic medina\, the city holds a unique place in Morocco’s cultu
 ral and spiritual landscape.Here\, participants will engage deeply with Gn
 awa music\, learning directly from local musicians about its ancestral roo
 ts\, ceremonial role\, and spiritual dimensions. Programming will also exp
 lore the Jewish history of Morocco\, with a focus on Essaouira’s once-th
 riving Jewish community and its enduring legacy.Time will be balanced betw
 een guided learning and open exploration—wandering the medina\, connecti
 ng with artisans\, and absorbing the creative\, contemplative energy that 
 defines the city. We'll eat well at every meal and enjoy the nightlife of 
 dancing and music in this lovely city.May 27–29: Retreat at an Eco-Perma
 culture Center in BoulouaneThe final phase of the Oliotrip brings the grou
 p inland to a riverside eco-permaculture retreat center in Boulouane\, off
 ering space for integration and grounding. Surrounded by nature\, these da
 ys are designed to slow the pace and synthesize the experiences of the pre
 vious week.&nbsp\;We will learn about local agricultural practices and foo
 d systems\, engage in a hands-on cooking workshop using ingredients grown 
 on site\, and share communal meals rooted in regional tradition. The journ
 ey concludes with a closing concert featuring a music group local to the a
 rea—bringing together land\, sound\, and collective experience as a mean
 ingful closing ritual.*Our group trip ends here but if you can swing it\, 
 we encourage you to travel to one of the old cities in Morocco (or return 
 to your favorite place from the Oliotrip) - we will be happy to offer some
  recommendations!&nbsp\;--Your Guide:Samir LanGus is a Grammy-nominated mu
 sician\, born and raised in the city of Agadir\, Morocco. Music has always
  been a part of the constant variety of street sounds of his city\, from m
 erchants to entertainers and calls to prayer. LanGus began learning Gnawa\
 , a traditional\, spiritual trance music\, at an early age from the Gnawa 
